          "body": "The word *keruv* (cherub) appears eight times in the chapter, distributed across three distinct locations: carved on the walls (3:7), sculpted in the round as free-standing figures in the Most Holy Place (3:10-13), and woven into the veil (3:14). The cherubim are not decorative motifs. In the Hebrew Bible, cherubim are the throne-guardians of divine majesty: they flank the mercy seat in the Tabernacle (Exodus 25:18-22), they appear in Ezekiel's throne-chariot vision (Ezekiel 1:5-14; 10), they stand at the entrance of Eden after the Fall (Genesis 3:24). Their presence throughout the Temple declares that this building is not a king's palace with a religious wing — it is the earthly footprint of the heavenly throne room. The two great cherubim in the Most Holy Place (3:10-13) span the full twenty-cubit width of the room with their wings, forming a canopy over the ark of the covenant. Their wingspan touches wall-to-wall: nothing within the Most Holy Place is outside the shadow of divine guardianship. The Chronicler's repeated return to the cherubim motif insists that the God of Israel is the same God who sits enthroned above the cherubim (Psalm 80:1; Isaiah 37:16) — and who now, astonishingly, has agreed to dwell among His people."
